After one month of trying out several options, here's how my rigged #ursaminipro #camera currently stands. Four qualities are paramount for me to make the decision of choosing any components for this rig: Reliability, control, effectiveness and adaptability. Even though this is my "big" #filmmaker camera, I want to be able to move around quite swiftly while feeling 100% confident of my hold while I shoot,  and be able to change camera setups in seconds, without having to worry about ANY of the accessories getting unplugged or worse yet, falling out. So, here's the #gear breakdown: I'll start with the brilliant @zacuto Gripper P-Tap adapter, which is mounted to one of their rods and is meant to declutter all the cables from the electronics mounted on the rig while unifying and simplifying their power feed. Next is @brighttangerine 's Titan arm, which is holding my AC7 monitor from @smallhd which has served me so well for years. This arm is simply fantastic! Super solid, strong grip and extremely adaptable; I can position my monitor anywhere I want/need with it. It also has some of the best quality build that I've seen. I simply can't shoot without it anymore! And speaking of control, on the top we have @woodencamera 's NATO handle, which is SUPERB! It's by far the most versatile handle I've ever seen, and I tried so many! Not only it's the one which gave me the best feel of grip, but it also has countless benefits, like its 15 and 19mm openings, its multitude of mounting points AND its amazing capability of being able to rotate 360 degrees. It's just fantastic. Period. I also used one of their rosette extensions, to protrude the @blackmagicdesign_news trigger handle further away from the main body. And everything is resting on @smallrigchina plates, which are well built and very smartly designed to accommodate tons of options. So there you go, that's the update for now on my #ursaminipro . Still plenty of pieces left to finish this "puzzle" but stay tuned if you're into #cameraporn #gearporn and #film . I've acquired all the gear you see here at @abelcine & @filmtools . Thank you both for leading the pack in #losangeles for all of our #filmmaking #filmgear needs!

"I began my photography journey with an action camera because I was interested in the distortion effect. But after a year, I got bored and got a DSLR for its flexibility and versatility. I can always change lenses and perspectives depending on the kind of shot I was planning. It took me about 2-3 months to save enough for the camera because I'm still a student. Now I use it to shoot mostly portraits and I'm eyeing the EF85mm f/1.8 USM to get better and sharper images with nice bokeh.” See the results of Luqman Nurhaqim's work at @luqmann_____ on Instagram, and tag us in photos of your Canon gear for a chance to be featured!
